omy of slavery. In Manet’s painting, Olympia and her maid represent objects of exchange, a commentary on the French Empire’s complicity in the ongoing slave trade in the Americas. Expertly researched and argued, this bold study reveals the extraordinary weight of history and politics that Manet’s painting bears. Locating the presence of slavery at modernism’s roots, Value in Art is a surprising and necessary intervention in our understanding of art history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArt and literaturezFrance. 0aArt and societyzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszFrance. 0aBlack people in art. 0aSlaveryzUnited StatesxForeign public opinion. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aÉdouard Manet, Émile Zola, Charles Baudelaire, Olympia, American Civil War, Uncle Tom's Cabin, cotton, slavery, value, U.S.S. Kearsarge.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226809960423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226809960/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles